occurrences.line_text: Doth belch out flames, and rockes in peeces broke,
And freely sprong out of the fruitfull ground,
Which whenas true by tryall he out fond,
Which long time had bene shut, and out of hond
Out of the East, with flaming lockes bedight,
Throwne out from womanish impatient mind?
Out of my way, through perils straunge and hard;
And often semblaunce made to scape out of their hand.
To beene departed out of Eden lands,
His artes he moues, and out of caytiues hands
Now therefore Ladie, rise out of your paine,
Brayes out her latest breath, and vp her eyes doth seele.
Out of her gored wound the cruell steele
That at the last she gan to breath out liuing aire.
As one out of a deadly dreame affright,
Betwixt them both can measure out a meane,
The dead knights sword out of his sheath he drew,
Welling out streames of teares, and quite dismayd
Did out of order stray about her daintie eares.
But poured out in pleasure and delight;
Was suddein vanished out of his sight:
And darted fyrie beames out of the same,
Out crying, ï¿½ what euer heauenly powre,
She staid: with that he crauld out of his nest,
And breathes out wrath and hainous crueltie;
Thereat he wondrous glad, out of the path
Can call out of the bodies of fraile wightes:
And now he has pourd out his idle mind
Did breath out bounteous smels, & painted colors shew.
Another her out boastes, and all for tryall strips.
And groneth out his vtmost grudging spright,
Suddeinly out of his delightfull dreame
Bene choisely picked out from all the rest,
To bud out faire, and her sweet smels throw all around.
Out of her fruitfull lap; how, no man knowes,
Whom neither wind out of their seat could forse,
Nor timely tides did driue out of their sluggish sourse.
That he awoke out of his idle dreme,
Harrow now out, and well away, he cryde,
That of my plenty poure out vnto all,
But gnawing Gealosie out of their sight
Like an huge caue, hewne out of rocky clift,
Not such, as earth out of her fruitfull woomb
Pourd out his life, and last Philosophy
Swift Atalanta, when through craft he her out ran.
The life did flit away out of her nest,
His Lords owne flesh. Therewith out of his hond
His cursed life out of her lodge haue rent:
Out of the wound the red bloud flowed fresh,
Breathing out wrath, and bellowing disdaine,
Breathd out his ghost, which to th'infernall shade
And all thy wrongs will wipe out of my souenaunce.
Out of the rockes and caues adioyning nye,
Out of the fennes of Allan do arise,
Nor wight, nor word mote passe out of the gate,
When cause requird, but neuer out of time;
It might breake out, and set the whole on fire,
It was auoided quite, and throwne out priuily.
They all attonce out of their seates arose,
The light goes out, and weeke is throwne away;
Cryde out, Deare countrey, Ã´ how dearely deare
Ere long they rowed were quite out of sight,
Some like wild Bores late rouzd out of the brakes;
As one awakt out of long slombring shade,
Out of his hold, and broke his caitiue bands,
Out of his swowne arose, fresh to contend,
When the hart bloud should gush out of his chest,
And hauing scruzd out of his carrion corse
Whiles the salt brine out of the billowes sprong.
A place pickt out by choice of best aliue,
Who taking it out of her tender hond,
Out of this fountaine, sweet and faire to see,
His deawy face out of the sea doth reare:
Tryde all her arts, & all her sleights, thence out to wrest.
All suddenly out of the thickest brush,
Breathing out beastly lust her to defile:
At last as nigh out of the wood she came,
Pourd out their plenty, without spight or spare:
Lightly arose out of her wearie bed,
Out of her quiet slomber did awake,
She lightly lept out of her filed bed,
Rashly out of their rouzed couches sprong,
Shortly they reard out of her frosen swownd;
Drew out a deadly bow and arrow keene,
Was all disperst out of the firmament,
To hunt out perils and aduentures hard,
The word gone out, she backe againe would call,
Yet she might all men vew out of her bowre?
Lookt foorth, as Phoebus face out of the east,
That oft out of her bed she did astart,
Feeling her leape out of her loathed nest,
Out of her daughters hart fond fancies to reuerse.
For he by words could call out of the sky
In vaine seekes wonders out of Magicke spell.
Shall spring, out of the auncient Troian blood,
What meanes shall she out seeke, or what wayes take?
From where the day out of the sea doth spring,
Out of their hollow bosome forth to throw
Soone as she vp out of her deadly fit
Could scarce recouered be out of her paine;
His deawy head out of the Ocean maine,
and reareth out of sownd.
Panting for breath, and almost out of hart,
Which way she fared hath, good Sir tell out of hand.
And out of sight escaped at the least;
For soone as he was vanisht out of sight,
Out of that forest should escape their might;
Anone one sent out of the thicket neare
And a large streame of bloud out of the wound did flow.
Out of her fleshly ferme fled to the place of paine.
And made him fast out of the forrest runne;
Who al this while lay bleeding out his hart-bloud neare.
And reskewed out of the heauy stownd.
And loue for to dislodge out of his nest:
Whence he it fetcht out of her natiue place,
Out of her heauy swowne not to awake,
By which both in and out men moten pas;
He letteth in, he letteth out to wend,
The state of life, out of the griesly shade.
The maistring raines out of her weary wrest,
With that adowne out of her Christall eyne
Eftsoones out of her hidden caue she cald
Ne her out of the stedfast sadle driued,
Out of his wauering seat him pluckt perforse,
Out of his dreame, that did him long entraunce,
To find them out. Mote I (then laughing sayd
The hart out of his brest: for sith her ded
That her out of astonishment he wrought,
And out of that same fishers filthy nest
Therein is eaten out an hollow caue,
And lose the teme out of his weary waine,
To keepe vs out, in scorne of his owne will,
That none him durst awake out of his dreme;
Now Bacchus fruit out of the siluer plate
Which well she red out of the learned line,
(Said he,) out of the flames for safegard fled,
And Troy againe out of her dust was reard,
Out of the Troians scattered of-spring,
Out of the goodly heauen amoued quight,
Out of his sight her selfe once to absent.
Out of the flames, which he had quencht whylere
With that out of his bouget forth he drew
Which when Malbecco saw, out of his bush
As one out of a dreame not waked well,
Out of the ruddy East was fully reard,
The heardes out of their foldes were loosed quight,
Out of his quiet slomber him abrade,
Out of her thraldome and continuall feare?
Cald by strong charmes out of eternall night,
Out of her secret stand, that day for to out weare.
Out of her secret stand, that day for to out weare.
A murdrous knife out of his pocket drew,
Full dreadfull things out of that balefull booke
And in sweete rauishment pourd out her spright:
Were kept, and yet that Knight not locked out:
So none should be out shut, sith all of loues were fitted.
Out of the dwellings of the damned sprights,
That none the same may easily out win;
Like shaft out of a bow preuenting speed.
By thousand furies, and from thence out throwen
Or answere for thy wrong, as shall fall out in fight.
As men awaked rashly out of dreme,
Out of their brests, that streames of bloud did rayle
And workes of noblest wits to nought out weare,
That none of them once out of order went,
And with vnwearied fingers drawing out
And eke so short, that seemd their ends out shortly came.
To draw them longer out, and better twine,
Out of his headpeece Cambell fiercely reft,
Both falling out doe stirre vp strifefull broyle,
The soule had sure out of his bodie riued,
He lightly lept out of his place of rest,
So did one soule out of his bodie flie
As one that had out of a dreame bene reard,
The one out of the swownd, which him did blend,
Towards them driuing like a storme out sent.
Eftsoones out of her Coch she gan auaile,
Their wrathfull blades downe fell out of their hand,
Which drawing softly forth out of the darke,
That all men threw out vowes and wishes vaine.
Out of the swowne, in which too long he lay;
Out of the field, that none perceiu'd it plaine.
To rescue Satyrane out of his pray;
Then rushed forth out of the thickest rout
So oftentimes he out of sleepe abrayd,
Out of the burning cinders, and therewith
And now the day out of the Ocean mayne
Lightly he started vp out of that stound,
Throwne out by angry Ioue in his vengeance,
And cruell sword out of his fingers slacke
And wiping out remembrance of all ill,
But when as I did out of sleepe abray,
But all she did was but to weare out day.
One rushing forth out of the thickest weed,
Her selfe downe soust, she waked out of dread
For wofull wight, chose out a gloomy glade,
To be embaulm'd, and sweat out dainty dew,
Wretchedly wearing out his youthly yeares,
That out of all mens knowledge he was worne at last.
And there out sucking venime to her parts entyre.
Pouring out streames of poyson and of gall
At last when they were passed out of sight,
To see his foe breath out his spright in vaine:
Out of his hands could not redeeme her gage,
Did secretly out of her prison steale;
Exchanged out of one into an other feare.
With feruent flames, and loued out of measure:
Out of their wretched corses, and their liues depriue.
Sends forth the winds out of his hidden threasure,
Of Ate and Duessa they fell out,
That through the clifts the vermeil bloud out sponne,
Faint friends when they fall out, most cruell fomen bee.
That warded all which in or out did wend,
Eftsoones out sprung two more of equall mould;
And either beat him in, or driue him out.
Out of her fruitfull lap aboundant flowres,
The spring breake forth out of his lusty bowres,
Chirpe loud to thee out of their leauy cages,
Out of his Albion did on dry-foot pas
And Conway which out of his streame doth send
Deliuer hence out of this dungeon strong,
Ne could by search nor any meanes out find
Through his disease, did by and by out find,
Me seemes the world is runne quite out of square,
Out of their proper places farre away,
And all things freely grew out of the ground:
And equitie to measure out along,
Ne any armour could his dint out ward,
With which he thresht out falshood, and did truth vnfould.
Bursting forth teares, like springs out of a banke,
And on his steed her set, to beare her out of sight.
That when he wak't out of his warelesse paine,
At length found out, whereas she hidden lay
And weighed out in ballaunces so nere,
And each estate quite out of order go'th?
But streight the winged words out of his ballaunce flew.
And chaced quite out of the field, that none
And drawing him out of the open hall,
And blotted out his armes with falshood blent,
And out of court him scourged openly.
Out of the foreside of their forgerie,
So each of them layd downe his sword out of his hand.
Him Talus tooke out of perplexitie,
She causeth them be hang'd vp out of hand;
So forth she came out of the citty gate,
Then forth came Artegall out of his tent,
Out of his breast the very heart haue rended:
Out of her steely armes were flashing seene,
That in and out thou mayst haue passage free.
Deuize how to enlarge him out of hould.
She thought to send some one to seeke him out;
And then againe resolu'd to hunt him out
Thus she all night wore out in watchfulnesse,
She forth yssew'd out of her loathed bowre,
And from her eies did flash out fiery light,
Your aide, to guide me out of errour blind.
The warlike Amazon out of her bowre did peepe.
And bore him quite out of his saddle, longer
Where when they saw their foes dead out of doubt,
Me like a dog she out of dores did thrust,
She threw her husbands murdred infant out,
Out of her fist the wicked weapon caught:
And breaking forth out at a posterne dore,
And brought the pillage home, whence none could get it out.
Can follow out those false footsteps of his,
To keepe out guyle, and malice, and despight,
Was raced out, and Mal was now put in.
Yet dropping fresh out of the Indian fount,
Out of the pleasant soyle, and citties glad,
But now by force extort out of her hand,
Out of their breasts, with furious despight.
And them conuayd out at a Posterne dore.
Till ye haue rooted all the relickes out
Out of her poysnous entrails, fraught with dire decay.
And the third time out of an hidden shade,
Or reaue out of the hand, that did it hend.
Strongly he stroue out of her greedy gripe
And powred out of her infernall sinke
Breathing out clouds of sulphure fowle and blacke,
Then all the rest burst out to all outragiousnesse.
Long while he tug'd and stroue, to get it out,
To search out those, that vsd to rob and steale,
To find him out, yet still I forward trace.
Cryde out, Ah mercie Sir, doe me not slay,
Out of the countrie wherein I was bred,
Like one that out of deadly dreame awooke:
All sodainely out of the forrest nere
But laught them out, as if his greater pryde
That forth out of an hill fresh gushing did appere.
And shrieked out, a thing vncomely for a knight.
Him selfe out of the forest he did wynd,
Her to recure out of that stony swound,
And plucke the pray oftimes out of their greedy hould.
Out of their ambush broke, and gan him to inuade.
And sparkling fire out of his furious eyne,
To thrust him out of dore, doing his worst assay.
Therefore so soone as he was out of vew,
Cryde out aloud for mercie him to saue;
The Saluage forth out of the wood issew'd
And throwing downe his load out of his hand,
Where still he lay, ne out of swoune awooke,
Complayning out on me, that would not on them rew.
That all which I put in, fals out anon;
Or suffer her out of her sleepe to wake,
Sleepe out her fill, without encomberment:
Benumbes her cheekes: Then out aloud she cries,
Readie to launce her brest, and let out loued life.
By any skill out of his cruell hands;
And out of them to presse the milke: loue so much could.
Out of the wood he rose, and toward them did go.
The vanisht all away out of his sight,
A Tigre forth out of the wood did rise,
Appeard for people in nor out to pas,
The theeues fall out for Pastorell,
Out quenched, leaues no skill nor difference of wight.
To sparke out litle beames, like starres in foggie night.
Die? out alas! then Calidore did cry:
Though out of course, yet hath not bene mis-sayd,
That spat out poyson and gore bloudy gere
That he gan fret and fome out bloudy gore,
Out of their townes did round about him throng,
Which to outbarre, with painefull pyonings
That signe of last outbreathed life did seeme,
Of that same outcast carkasse, that erewhile
And make his carkasse as the outcast dong?
All as a blazing starre doth farre outcast
And pitty much his plight, that liu'd like outcast thrall.
There they him left a carrion outcast;
With yelling outcries, and with shrieking sowne;
Who when those pittifull outcries he heard,
Ran forth in hast with hideous outcry,
Her shrill outcryes and shriekes so loud did bray,
And each did striue the other to out-goe,
Appear'd in place, the which each other did outgoe.
Which still increast, till she her terme had full outgone.
When Iustice was not for most meed outhyred,
He could outlearne, he them from ground did reare:
Hath outrag'd you, and thrald your gentle make.
Hart cannot thinke, what outrage, and what cryes,
To flie the vengeance for his outrage dew;
And playnd of grieuous outrage, which he red
The strong extremities of their outrage;
And with importune outrage him assayld;
First praise of knighthood is, foule outrage to deface.
As to doen outrage to a sleeping ghost:
Which outrage when those gentle knights did see,
And into termes of open outrage brust,
Nor so fowle outrage doen by liuing men:
Of whose foule outrage they impatient,
And her to saue from outrage, meekely prayed him.
Through open outrage he her bore away,
And hatefull outrage long him chaced thus;
The wrongfull outrage of vnrighteous men,
To giue him the reward for such vile outrage dew.
The noble Argonauts to outrage fell:
Of outrage for the words, which she heard say,
The outrage of his furious fit relented.
Haue rays'd this cruell warre and outrage fell,
To worke such outrage on so faire a creature?
That had done outrage in so high degree:
In friends profest, and so great outrage donne:
From such foule outrage, and them long forbore:
To cease his outrage, and him faire besought,
And more increast her outrage mercilesse,
In crueltie and outrage she did pas,
For soone as he their outrage backe doth beat,
Them also gan assaile with outrage bold,
Can keepe from outrage, and from doing wrong,
Which cruell outrage when as Artegall
Meane while his Ladie, which this outrage saw,
Which had this outrage wrought with wicked hand.
That th'outrage of his violence he stayd,
And heauenly virgin thus outraged see,
He that faire Vna late fowle outraged,
With rigour so outrageous he smitt,
As her outrageous foe had left her late,
But with outrageous strokes did him restraine,
And smote againe with more outrageous might;
Prouoking him by her outrageous talke,
For when the cause of that outrageous deede
Outrageous anger, and woe-working iarre,
Outrageous wrong, and hellish couetize,
But all so soone as his outrageous powre
Who, had he not with wrath outrageous,
They reard a most outrageous dreadfull yelling cry,
The cause of their dissention and outrageous yre.
Through thy strong buffets and outrageous blowes,
And oft him threatned death for his outrageous wrong.
And shortly grew into outrageous fire;
To saue her selfe from that outrageous spoyle,
That striue and storme with stirre outrageous,
To fly his stepdames loues outrageous,
But for vyld treasons, and outrageous shame,
But he, the more outrageous and bold,
And strooke, and foynd, and lasht outrageously,
Of many beasts, that roard outrageously,
So sore, and with foule outrages opprest:
And rusht vpon him with outragious pride;
Thus as he spoke, loe with outragious cry
Into outragious flames vnwares did grow,
Is with the blast of some outragious storme
And all her people murdred with outragious might.
And by outragious force away did beare:
Him follow'd, by the tract of his outragious spoile.
Outragiously, as they enraged were,
Then all the rest burst out to all outragiousnesse.
Till they outraigned had their vtmost date,
But he them both outran a wondrous space,
For ere two hundred yeares be full outronne,
That seemed to outshine the dimmed skye,
Deuoid of outward sense, and natiue strength,
Ne was there outward breach, nor grudge in hart,
The outward sparkes of her in burning fire;
That from like inward fire that outward smoke had steemd.
But th'only forme and outward fashion;
But shewd by outward signes, that dread her sence did daze.
And outward shew faire semblance they did beare;
Like knight aduenturous in outward vew,
Weend as he said, by that her outward grace,
And yet vncertaine by such outward sight,
Who through the likenesse of my outward hew,
Yet seem'd full aged by his outward sight,
By outward signes, (as well he might) did see,
By outward shew her inward sence defining.
For of a Mayd she had the outward face,
And not in outward shows, but inward thoughts defynd.
First learne your outward sences to refraine
For from those outward sences ill affected,
Then outward salues, that may augment it more.
Yet outwardly some little comfort shewes:
That like a litle forrest seemed outwardly.
The faire Poeana; who seemes outwardly
Yet chearefull signes he shewed outwardly.
Thus did the Prince that wearie night outweare,
The sparks soone quench, the springing seed outweed,
His fattie waues do fertile slime outwell,
Yet fled she fast, and both them farre outwent,
As by no meanes he can himselfe outwind.
All that day she outwore in wandering,
And when my weary ghost with griefe outworne,
Till that the truth thereof I did outwrest,
For now three dayes of men were full outwrought,
The Ouze, whom men doe Isis rightly name;
She wore, with crownes and owches garnished,
Adornd with gemmes and owches wondrous faire,
Gold, amber, yuorie, perles, owches, rings,
Which I do owe vnto all woman kind,
To her I homage and my seruice owe,
Then to him said, Liue and allegaunce owe,
How much to her we owe, that all vs gaue,
All little Riuers, which owe vassallage
To Maydenhead and noble knighthood owe,
And kept from complishing the faith, which I did owe.
Of rudenesse, for not yeelding what they owe:
The messenger of death, the ghastly Owle
On top whereof aye dwelt the ghastly Owle,
The ill-faste Owle, deaths dreadfull messengere,
And now the crowing Cocke, and now the Owle
And after him Owles and Night-rauens flew,
Apes, Lions, ï¿½/-gles, Owles, fooles, louers, children, Dames.
Headed like Owles, with beckes vncomely bent,
Fro[m] her own worship, they her Asse would worship fayn.
Go find some other play-fellowes, mine own sweet boy.
That what the sea vnto you sent, your own should seeme.
That what the sea vnto you sent, your own should seeme.
Sith his own thought he knew most cleare from wite.
With which he drew him forth, euen in his own despight.
That makes them doubt, their wits be not their owne:
Your owne deare sake forst me at first to leaue
Astonied with the stroke of their owne hand,
To get, and nightly feare to lose his owne,
But inwardly he chawed his owne maw
Of proud Lucifera, and his owne companie.
Forgetfull of his owne, that mindes anothers cares.
Shall with his owne bloud price that he hath spilt.
With sonnes owne blade, her fowle reproches spoke;
But for his loue, and for her owne selfe sake,
His owne faire Dryope now he thinkes not faire,
That his owne sire and maister of his guise
So oft as he through his owne foolish pride,
All wallowd in his owne fowle bloudy gore,
All wallowd in his owne yet luke-warme blood,
With thine owne bloud to price his bloud, here shed in sight.
But his owne guiltie mind deseruing death.
O foolish men, why haste ye to your owne decay?
And rend his flesh, and his owne synewes eat.
His owne deare Vna hearing euermore
His owne coate he would cut, and it distribute glad.
The wondrous workemanship of Gods owne mould,
Shalt be a Saint, and thine owne nations frend
Ne wonder; for her owne deare loued knight,
His owne two hands the holy knots did knit,
His owne two hands, for such a turne most fit,
And thine owne realmes in lond of Faery,
That me he knew not, neither his owne ille;
To magnifie his owne. But when they heard,
And in excesse exceeded her owne might;
In his owne kind he gan him selfe vnfold:
Where left, he went, and his owne false part playd,
Or bide the chaunce at thine owne ieoperdie.
